  "prompt": "Is the activity of money laundering prohibited?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is **prohibited** and considered a **serious criminal offense** in virtually all jurisdictions worldwide. Money laundering involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or organized crime) to make it appear as if it came from legitimate sources. This activity undermines the integrity of financial systems and facilitates further criminal behavior.\n\n### Why is it prohibited?\n1. **Illicit Activity**: Money laundering is inherently tied to illegal activities, which are harmful to society.\n2. **Economic Distortion**: It distorts economies by introducing \"dirty money\" into legitimate financial systems.\n3. **Crime Financing**: It enables criminals to fund further illegal activities.\n4. **Undermining Institutions**: It threatens the stability and trust in financial institutions and governments.\n\n### Legal Framework\nMost countries have strict anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations in place. For example:\n- The **United States** enforces AML laws under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Patriot Act**.\n- The **European Union** has implemented AML directives to unify regulations across member states.\n- Globally, organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set international standards to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n### Penalties\nPenalties for money laundering can include:\n- Heavy fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Seizure of assets\n- Reputational damage for individuals and institutions involved.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is not only prohibited but actively monitored and penalized by governments and financial institutions worldwide.",
